Here is an example Arduino code for controlling a continuous rotation stepper motor with a potentiometer:

```arduino
// Define the stepper motor pins
const int StepPin = 2;      // pin for driving the step pin of the stepper motor
const int DirPin = 3;       // pin for driving the direction pin of the stepper motor
const int EnablePin = 4;    // pin for enabling the stepper motor

// Define the potentiometer pin
const int PotPin = A0;      // pin for reading the potentiometer value

// Global variables
int PotValue = 0;           // variable to store the potentiometer value
int MotorSpeed = 0;         // variable to store the motor speed
int MotorDirection = 0;     // variable to store the motor direction

void setup() {
  // Set the stepper motor pins as outputs
  pinMode(StepPin, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(DirPin, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(EnablePin, OUTPUT);

  // Set the potentiometer pin as input
  pinMode(PotPin, INPUT);

  // Enable the stepper motor
  digitalWrite(EnablePin, LOW);
}

void loop() {
  // Read the potentiometer value
  PotValue = analogRead(PotPin);

  // Map the potentiometer value to motor speed (0-255)
  MotorSpeed = map(PotValue, 0, 1023, 0, 255);

  // Set the motor direction based on the potentiometer value
  if (PotValue < 512) {
    MotorDirection = 0;     // clockwise
  }
  else {
    MotorDirection = 1;     // counter-clockwise
  }

  // Set the direction pin of the stepper motor
  digitalWrite(DirPin, MotorDirection);

  // Drive the stepper motor based on the motor speed
  for (int i = 0; i < 200; i++) {
    digitalWrite(StepPin, HIGH);
    delayMicroseconds(5000 / MotorSpeed);
    digitalWrite(StepPin, LOW);
    delayMicroseconds(5000 / MotorSpeed);
  }
}
```

In this code, we use analogRead() to read the potentiometer value, and then map() to map the potentiometer value to a motor speed between 0-255. We also set the motor direction based on the potentiometer value.

We then use a for loop to generate the required number of steps for our stepper motor. The delay between the HIGH and LOW signals sent to the stepper motor is calculated based on the motor speed.

Note: The step and direction pins on your stepper motor driver may be different, so make sure to adjust them accordingly in the code. Also, test the code with a low current to avoid damaging the stepper motor driver.

Here's an example Arduino code for controlling a continuous rotation stepper motor with a potentiometer using the ContinuousStepper library:

```arduino
#include <ContinuousStepper.h> 

// Define the stepper motor pins
const int StepPin = 2;      // pin for driving the step pin of the stepper motor
const int DirPin = 3;       // pin for driving the direction pin of the stepper motor
const int EnablePin = 4;    // pin for enabling the stepper motor

// Define the potentiometer pin
const int PotPin = A0;      // pin for reading the potentiometer value

// Create a ContinuousStepper object
ContinuousStepper Motor(StepPin, DirPin);

// Global variables
